<DOC><DOCNO> AP890110-0249 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0507EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   01-10 0505</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0528</SECOND><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of the National Mediation Board haltedtalks between Eastern Airlines and its largest union and returned toWashington.   Chairman Walter Wallace couldn't be reached for comment, but anEastern executive said Monday Wallace gave as his reason the failureof efforts to keep secret the talks with the Machinists union.   Wallace arrived Friday for the talks at a hotel in Key Largo,Fla. The sessions were aimed at ending a contract stalemate that hasclouded the future of the airline, which is a subsidiary ofHouston-based Texas Air Corp.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   British electronics giant General Electric Co. PLCaccused rival Plessey Co. of mounting ``a spoiling tactic'' byjoining an international consortium that is expected to make ahostile bid for GEC.   GEC had joined Siemens AG of West Germany in launching a hostile,$3 billion offer for Plessey in November. Now GEC finds itself thetarget of a possible counter-bid by a consortium that probably willinclude Plessey.   GEC said Monday it would fight the possible counter-bid andpursue its efforts with Siemens to take over Plessey.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More U.S. companies changed their names in 1988than at any time in the past 19 years, and more than half thechanges resulted from corporate mergers and takeovers, acorporate-identity firm says.   The number of companies changing names last year was 1,864, or 6percent more than the 1,753 that changed names in 1987, the previousrecord year, the firm Anspach Grossman Portugal Inc. said Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   GTE Corp. announced a reorganization intosix operating groups and the appointment of Kent B. Foster aspresident of the largest group, GTE Telephone Operations.   GTE Chairman and Chief Executive Officer James. L. Johnson saidMonday the six operating groups will report to President and ChiefOperating Officer Charles R. Lee.   Johnson said the new corporate structure was ``a natural step inthe evolution of a more streamlined and efficient GTE, and isreflective of of the constantly changing business environment.''</TEXT><DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   State officials reacted cautiously to theannouncement that Pacific Resources Inc., Hawaii's second-largestpublicly held company, has agreed to be acquired by Australia'slargest company for nearly $400 million.   Gov. John Waihee said Monday the state will look closely at theagreement for Pacific Resources to be merged with Broken HillProprietary Co. Ltd.   Broken Hill wants to combine its own petroleum exploration anddevelopment business with the refining and marketing operations ofPacific Resources.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market gained ground for the fourth straight sessionMonday as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.17 to2,199.46, a new high since the 1987 crash.   The dollar rose but, finished below its highs of the day becauseof intervention by several central banks.   Bond prices were mixed.   Coffee, frozen pork-belly and soybean futures prices fellsharply, precious metals were mixed, energy futures rose andstock-index futures advanced.</TEXT></DOC>